Incident Response > [T4]: Post Evidence Collection Containment

Post Evidence Collection Containment

After collecting digital evidence, we should always take the compromised machine offline. Sometimes, shutting down the system or disconnecting it from the network is unacceptable for business operations. In that case, we can execute additional containment actions that keep the system online and temporarily safe, buying us more time until a replacement becomes ready.

Typical containment actions performed in that phase are:

  • Patching the exploited vulnerability
  • Killing the malware running process
  • Disabling compromised accounts
  • Malware removal
     

The vital thing to note is that there is no pre-defined static list of actions to execute in each phase, and what you do depends heavily on the context. Anything that can stop the attack without impacting forensic evidence should be done first. The rest can be done at the end. For example, deploying a firewall rule to block malware communications can be implemented in the pre-evidence collection phase if it will not impact attack artifacts. Otherwise, consider doing it after evidence collection.

In recent years, endpoint security solutions, EDR and XDR, started to include containment options to help defenders automate containment activities. For example, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint provides the option to contain or isolate a machine from the network.

Figure 


Crowdstrike Falcon also provides the ability to contain a compromised machine.

More details can be found here - How to Network Contain an Endpoint with Falcon Endpoint Protection.


Working under fire is challenging. Therefore, you should practice containment activities many times before experiencing a breach. A backup plan and tabletop exercises are very beneficial and prepare responders to handle and contain incidents efficiently. System owners should be aware of the containment action executed by the response team, keep them posted, and get their permission before any activity impacts operations.
